zing a dream of seeing China; a Peace Corps worker in Kenya. All can benefit from documenting their adventures, whether on paper or online. Through practical advice and adaptable exercises, this guide will help travelers hone their observational skills, conduct research and interviews, choose an appropriate literary form, and incorporate photos and videos into their writing. Writing about travel is more than just safeguarding memories—it can transform experiences and tease out new realizations. With Writing Abroad, travelers will be able to deepen their understanding of other cultures and write about that new awareness in clear and vivid prose.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aTravel writingvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aTravel writingxHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aTravel writing. 7aTravel / General.2bisacsh  aabroad.  adiverse cultures.  adocumentary.  aethnography.  afieldwork.  anonfiction.  aprofessionals.  asocial media.  astudents.  awriting strategies.1 aMulcahy, Joanne B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226444529423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226444529.jpg  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles